      "description": "Photographic and performative reinterpretation of Abaporu (1928), by Tarsila do Amaral. Through self-representation, contemporary photography and post-conceptual strategies, the work dialogues with the genealogy of appropriation art, visual citation and Brazilian modernism, while operating through imagetic disappropriation and cultural autophagy as a critical reflection on the circulation of images, cultural memory and the updating of visual repertoires.",
